<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[120,1225,876,1538]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">DIAGNOSIS: Females have the squiggled anterior receptaculum forming a rectangle; the T-shaped anterior process has an enlarged base and elongated arms (figs. 178, 179).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="23.[120,1225,876,1538]" box="[168,378,1175,1201]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">MALE: Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[120,1225,876,1538]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
FEMALE (PBI_ 
<accessionNumber box="[342,490,1212,1239]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/OON12513" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">OON 12513</accessionNumber>
, figs. 173–179): Total length 2.08. Carapace pale orange, elevated portion of pars cephalica finely reticulate, sides finely reticulate. Sternum pale orange, finely reticulate. Mouthparts orange. Abdomen without dark markings. Scutopedicel region with three faint ridges at sides only. Dorsal scutum pale orange, reticulate, covering full length of abdomen, no soft tissue visible from above. Postepigastric scutum pale orange, short, almost rectangular, covering about ¾ of abdomen length. Squiggled portion of anterior duct forming rectangle; T-shaped process with widened base, long branches.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[120,1225,876,1538]" box="[168,606,1474,1500]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">OTHER MATERIAL EXAMINED: None.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
